{"title_page": "The Witch's Trance-Dance", "text_new": "{{Infobox short story | <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]] or [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Books]] -->\n| name          = The Witch's Trance-Dance\n| image         = File:The Witch's Trance-Dance.png\n| caption       = 19th-century illustration from ''Xiangzhu liaozhai zhiyi tuyong'' (''Liaozhai Zhiyi'' with commentary and illustrations; 1886)\n| title_orig    = {{lang|zh|\u8df3\u795e}} (Huapi)\n| translator    = Sidney Sondergard (2008)\n| author        = [[Pu Songling]]\n| country       = China\n| language      = Chinese\n| series        = \n| genre         = {{Plainlist|\n* ''[[Zhiguai]]''\n* ''[[Chuanqi (short story)|Chuanqi]]''\n* [[Short story]]}}\n| published_in  = ''[[Strange Tales from a Chinese Studio]]''\n| publisher     = \n| media_type    = Print ([[Book]])\n| pub_date      = 1740\n| english_pub_date = \n| preceded_by   = [[Zhangcheng]] ({{lang|zh|\u5f20\u8bda}})\n| followed_by   = [[Iron Skin Method]] ({{lang|zh|\u94c1\u5e03\u886b\u6cd5}})\n}}\n\n\"'''The Witch's Trance-Dance'''\" ({{zh|s=\u8df3\u795e|t=\u8df3\u795e|p=Ti\u00e0oshen|l=Jumping God}}) is a [[short story]] by [[Pu Songling]] first published in ''[[Strange Tales from a Chinese Studio]]''.\n\n==Plot==\nIn [[Jinan]], and even more so in [[Beijing]], elderly female [[Wu (shaman)|shaman]]s are often invited to sick beds to perform a ritual known as ''tiaoshen'' ({{lang|zh|\u8df3\u795e}}) intended to drive away the illness; they are also asked to bless newly-weds. Pu Songling goes on to describe in detail the practices of these witches.\n\n==Literary significance==\nSidney Sondergard writes that \"there is certainly nothing sectarian about Pu Songling's depiction of the deities of [[Buddhism]] and [[Daoism]], which is keeping with his eclectic enthusiasm for all things beyond the mundane\"; in \"The Witch's Trance-Dance\", he \"open-mindedly depicts practices associated with [[folk religion|folk belief]]s that aren't part of a preexisting religious system\".{{Sfn|Sondergard|2008|p=xxvii}} Ma Ruifang likewise notes the vivid description of northern Chinese withcraft in the story, while arguing that Pu is satirising the fraudulent practices of the witches.{{Sfn|Ma|2004|p=485}}\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|script-title=zh:\u4ece\u300a\u804a\u658b\u5fd7\u5f02\u300b\u5230\u300a\u7ea2\u697c\u68a6\u300b|trans-title=From ''Strange Tales from a Chinese Studio'' to ''Dream of a Red Chamber''|isbn=9787532845040|first=Ruifang|last=Ma|year=2004|publisher=Shandong Jiaoyu|language=Chinese|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FSB1T-2A0jIC|title=Strange Tales from Liaozhai|last=Sondergard|first=Sidney|publisher=Jain Publishing Company|volume=3|isbn=9780895810458|year=2008|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{-}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Strange Tales from a Chinese Studio|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Witch's Trance-Dance, The}}\n[[Category:Stories within Strange Stories from a Chinese Studio]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox short story | <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]] or [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Books]] -->\n| name          = The Witch's Trance-Dance\n| image         = File:The Witch's Trance-Dance.png\n| caption       = 19th-century illustration from ''Xiangzhu liaozhai zhiyi tuyong'' (''Liaozhai Zhiyi'' with commentary and illustrations; 1886)\n| title_orig    = {{lang|zh|\u8df3\u795e}} (Huapi)\n| translator    = Sidney Sondergard (2008)\n| author        = [[Pu Songling]]\n| country       = China\n| language      = Chinese\n| series        = \n| genre         = {{Plainlist|\n* ''[[Zhiguai]]''\n* ''[[Chuanqi]]''\n* [[Short story]]}}\n| published_in  = ''[[Strange Tales from a Chinese Studio]]''\n| publisher     = \n| media_type    = Print ([[Book]])\n| pub_date      = 1740\n| english_pub_date = \n| preceded_by   = [[Zhangcheng]] ({{lang|zh|\u5f20\u8bda}})\n| followed_by   = [[Iron Skin Method]] ({{lang|zh|\u94c1\u5e03\u886b\u6cd5}})\n}}\n\n\"'''The Witch's Trance-Dance'''\" ({{zh|s=\u8df3\u795e|t=\u8df3\u795e|p=Ti\u00e0oshen|l=Jumping God}}) is a [[short story]] by [[Pu Songling]] first published in ''[[Strange Tales from a Chinese Studio]]''.\n\n==Plot==\nIn [[Jinan]], and even more so in [[Beijing]], elderly female [[Wu (shaman)|shaman]]s are often invited to sick beds to perform a ritual known as ''tiaoshen'' ({{lang|zh|\u8df3\u795e}}) intended to drive away the illness; they are also asked to bless newly-weds. Pu Songling goes on to describe in detail the practices of these witches.\n\n==Literary significance==\nSidney Sondergard writes that \"there is certainly nothing sectarian about Pu Songling's depiction of the deities of [[Buddhism]] and [[Daoism]], which is keeping with his eclectic enthusiasm for all things beyond the mundane\"; in \"The Witch's Trance-Dance\", he \"open-mindedly depicts practices associated with [[folk religion|folk belief]]s that aren't part of a preexisting religious system\".{{Sfn|Sondergard|2008|p=xxvii}} Ma Ruifang likewise notes the vivid description of northern Chinese withcraft in the story, while arguing that Pu is satirising the fraudulent practices of the witches.{{Sfn|Ma|2004|p=485}}\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|script-title=zh:\u4ece\u300a\u804a\u658b\u5fd7\u5f02\u300b\u5230\u300a\u7ea2\u697c\u68a6\u300b|trans-title=From ''Strange Tales from a Chinese Studio'' to ''Dream of a Red Chamber''|isbn=9787532845040|first=Ruifang|last=Ma|year=2004|publisher=Shandong Jiaoyu|language=Chinese|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FSB1T-2A0jIC|title=Strange Tales from Liaozhai|last=Sondergard|first=Sidney|publisher=Jain Publishing Company|volume=3|isbn=9780895810458|year=2008|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{-}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Strange Tales from a Chinese Studio|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Witch's Trance-Dance, The}}\n[[Category:Stories within Strange Stories from a Chinese Studio]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toChuanqi(link changed toChuanqi (short story)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Witch%27s_Trance-Dance"}
{"title_page": "The Fighting Cricket", "text_new": "{{Infobox short story | <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]] or [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Books]] -->\n| name          = The Fighting Cricket\n| image         = File:The Fighting Cricket.png\n| caption       = 19th-century illustration from ''Xiangzhu liaozhai zhiyi tuyong'' (''Liaozhai Zhiyi'' with commentary and illustrations; 1886)\n| title_orig    = {{lang|zh|\u4fc3\u7ec7}} (Cuzhi)\n| translator    = \n| author        = [[Pu Songling]]\n| country       = China\n| language      = Chinese\n| series        = \n| genre         = {{Plainlist|\n* ''[[Chuanqi (short story)|Chuanqi]]''\n* [[Short story]]}}\n| published_in  = ''[[Strange Tales from a Chinese Studio]]''\n| publisher     = \n| pub_date      = 1740\n| english_pub_date = \n| preceded_by   = [[Gongsun Jiuniang]] ({{lang|zh|\u516c\u5b59\u4e5d\u5a18}})\n| followed_by   = [[Liu Xiucai]] ({{lang|zh|\u67f3\u79c0\u624d}})\n}}\n\n\"'''The Fighting Cricket'''\" ({{zh|p=C\u00f9zhi|s=\u4fc3\u7ec7|t=\u4fc3\u7e54}}) is a [[short story]] by [[Pu Songling]] first published in ''[[Strange Tales from a Chinese Studio]]''. Set in a society whose emperor has an obsession with fighting crickets, the story follows a boy who metamorphoses into one such cricket to save his father.\n\n==Publication history==\nThe story was originally titled \"Cuzhi\" ({{lang|zh|\u4fc3\u7e54}}) and first appeared in Pu Songling's anthology of supernatural tales, ''Strange Tales from a Chinese Studio'' (''Liaozhai'') published in 1740. It was first translated into English as \"The Fighting Cricket\" by the British [[sinologist]] [[Herbert A. Giles]] and was included in his 1880 translation of ''Strange Tales''. It reappeared with modifications in a subsequent edition, published in 1908.{{Sfn|Giles|2011|p=254}} \n\n==Inspiration==\n[[Cricket fighting]] was commonplace during the [[Qing dynasty]] which Pu lived in, with established clubs in the more developed cities like [[Beijing]], [[Tianjin]], and [[Shanghai]]. Pu evidently drew some inspiration from the [[Ming dynasty]] guidebook to [[Beijing]] titled ''A Brief Guide to Sights in the Capital'', having published a condensed version of it with a foreword of his own. Technical details found in ''A Brief Guide'', like the diet of a cricket and the different types of cricket, are incorporated in Pu's short story, while other phrases in the guidebook are copied verbatim. Pu's \"connoisseurship\" and the influence of specialised handbooks on him can also be seen in another ''Strange Tales'' story titled \"[[A Strange Matter Concerning Pigeons]]\" which revolves around [[pigeon]]s instead of crickets.{{Sfn|Zeitlin|1997|pp=71\u201372}} \n\n==Themes and analysis==\nAdrian Hsia argues that in \"The Fighting Cricket\", Pu is rallying against the unfair treatment of the peasants that he would have personally witnessed: \"The fighting cricket is a sign of the inhuman exploitation through taxes which can destroy every family.\"{{Sfn|Hsia|1996|pp=150\u2013155}} He likens the story to \"[[The Metamorphosis]]\" by [[Franz Kafka]], pointing out that both works \"create, through their animal figures, an artistic world which is parallel to the human world\"{{Sfn|Hsia|1996|p=175}} while adding that the \"affinity\" between the two stories was \"striking\" to Chinese critics.{{Sfn|Hsia|1996|p=192}}\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|first=Herbert A.|last=Giles|title=Strange Tales from a Chinese Studio: The Classic Collection of Eerie and Fantastic Chinese Stories of the Supernatural|year=2011|orig-year=1878|location=Clarendon, Verm.|publisher=Tuttle Publishing|isbn=9781462900732|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|title=Kafka and China|isbn=9783906755830|year=1996|publisher=Lang|ref=harv|first=Adrian|last=Hsia}}\n* {{cite book|title=Historian of the Strange: Pu Songling and the Chinese Classical Tale|first=Judith T.|last=Zeitlin|year=1997|location=Palo Alto|publisher=Stanford University Press|isbn=9780804729680|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/historianofstran00judi}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{-}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Strange Tales from a Chinese Studio|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fighting Cricket, The}}\n[[Category:Stories within Strange Stories from a Chinese Studio]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox short story | <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]] or [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Books]] -->\n| name          = The Fighting Cricket\n| image         = File:The Fighting Cricket.png\n| caption       = 19th-century illustration from ''Xiangzhu liaozhai zhiyi tuyong'' (''Liaozhai Zhiyi'' with commentary and illustrations; 1886)\n| title_orig    = {{lang|zh|\u4fc3\u7ec7}} (Cuzhi)\n| translator    = \n| author        = [[Pu Songling]]\n| country       = China\n| language      = Chinese\n| series        = \n| genre         = {{Plainlist|\n* ''[[Chuanqi]]''\n* [[Short story]]}}\n| published_in  = ''[[Strange Tales from a Chinese Studio]]''\n| publisher     = \n| pub_date      = 1740\n| english_pub_date = \n| preceded_by   = [[Gongsun Jiuniang]] ({{lang|zh|\u516c\u5b59\u4e5d\u5a18}})\n| followed_by   = [[Liu Xiucai]] ({{lang|zh|\u67f3\u79c0\u624d}})\n}}\n\n\"'''The Fighting Cricket'''\" ({{zh|p=C\u00f9zhi|s=\u4fc3\u7ec7|t=\u4fc3\u7e54}}) is a [[short story]] by [[Pu Songling]] first published in ''[[Strange Tales from a Chinese Studio]]''. Set in a society whose emperor has an obsession with fighting crickets, the story follows a boy who metamorphoses into one such cricket to save his father.\n\n==Publication history==\nThe story was originally titled \"Cuzhi\" ({{lang|zh|\u4fc3\u7e54}}) and first appeared in Pu Songling's anthology of supernatural tales, ''Strange Tales from a Chinese Studio'' (''Liaozhai'') published in 1740. It was first translated into English as \"The Fighting Cricket\" by the British [[sinologist]] [[Herbert A. Giles]] and was included in his 1880 translation of ''Strange Tales''. It reappeared with modifications in a subsequent edition, published in 1908.{{Sfn|Giles|2011|p=254}} \n\n==Inspiration==\n[[Cricket fighting]] was commonplace during the [[Qing dynasty]] which Pu lived in, with established clubs in the more developed cities like [[Beijing]], [[Tianjin]], and [[Shanghai]]. Pu evidently drew some inspiration from the [[Ming dynasty]] guidebook to [[Beijing]] titled ''A Brief Guide to Sights in the Capital'', having published a condensed version of it with a foreword of his own. Technical details found in ''A Brief Guide'', like the diet of a cricket and the different types of cricket, are incorporated in Pu's short story, while other phrases in the guidebook are copied verbatim. Pu's \"connoisseurship\" and the influence of specialised handbooks on him can also be seen in another ''Strange Tales'' story titled \"[[A Strange Matter Concerning Pigeons]]\" which revolves around [[pigeon]]s instead of crickets.{{Sfn|Zeitlin|1997|pp=71\u201372}} \n\n==Themes and analysis==\nAdrian Hsia argues that in \"The Fighting Cricket\", Pu is rallying against the unfair treatment of the peasants that he would have personally witnessed: \"The fighting cricket is a sign of the inhuman exploitation through taxes which can destroy every family.\"{{Sfn|Hsia|1996|pp=150\u2013155}} He likens the story to \"[[The Metamorphosis]]\" by [[Franz Kafka]], pointing out that both works \"create, through their animal figures, an artistic world which is parallel to the human world\"{{Sfn|Hsia|1996|p=175}} while adding that the \"affinity\" between the two stories was \"striking\" to Chinese critics.{{Sfn|Hsia|1996|p=192}}\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|first=Herbert A.|last=Giles|title=Strange Tales from a Chinese Studio: The Classic Collection of Eerie and Fantastic Chinese Stories of the Supernatural|year=2011|orig-year=1878|location=Clarendon, Verm.|publisher=Tuttle Publishing|isbn=9781462900732|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|title=Kafka and China|isbn=9783906755830|year=1996|publisher=Lang|ref=harv|first=Adrian|last=Hsia}}\n* {{cite book|title=Historian of the Strange: Pu Songling and the Chinese Classical Tale|first=Judith T.|last=Zeitlin|year=1997|location=Palo Alto|publisher=Stanford University Press|isbn=9780804729680|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/historianofstran00judi}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{-}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Strange Tales from a Chinese Studio|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fighting Cricket, The}}\n[[Category:Stories within Strange Stories from a Chinese Studio]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toChuanqi(link changed toChuanqi (short story)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Fighting_Cricket"}
